ames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"York","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of York in northern England. The surname is now widespread throughout England. Originally, the city bore the Latin name <i>Eburacum</i>, which is probably from a Brittonic name meaning ‘yew-tree place’. This was altered by folk etymology to Old English <i>Eoforwīc</i> (from the elements <i>eofor</i> ‘wild boar’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘specialized farmstead’). This name was taken over by Scandinavian settlers, who altered it back to opacity in the form <i>Jórvík</i> or <i>Jórk</i> (English <i>York</i>, which became finally settled as the placename in the 13th century). The surname has also been adopted by Jews as an Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames.","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of the East Slavic patronymic   Yurkovich   or its Croatian, Slovak, or Slovenian variants. Compare   Yurk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Yurkovich","meanings":["Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Yurkovych</b>) and Belorussian: patronymic from the personal name   Yurko   and its Belorussian equivalent <i>Yurka</i>, pet forms of Ukrainian <i>Yuriy</i> and Belorussian <i>Yuray</i>, equivalents of Greek <i>Geōrgios</i> (see   George  ).","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Jurković</b>, Slovak and Slovenian <b>Jurkovič</b> (see   Jurkovic  , compare   Jurkovich   and   Yurkovic  ).","Jewish (from Bessarabia): habitational name for someone from Yurkovtsy in Ukraine."]},{"name":"Yorke","meanings":["English: variant of   York  ."]},{"name":"Yorks","meanings":["English: variant of   York  ."]}]},{"name":"Yvette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine diminutive form of   Yves  , now also established in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Yvette de York was born about 1094, in Halsham, Yorkshire, England. She married Guillaume d'Arques in 1115, in Newton, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1152, in Thorp Arch, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 60, and was buried in Guisborough, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1094–about 1152":"umbes 1094–umbes 1152","1095–1154":"1095–1154","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1137–1206":"1137–1206","1094–1152":"1094–1152","about 1094":"umbes 1094","1132":"1132","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1206":"1206","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1137":"1137","Abt 1132":"umbes 1132","about 1152":"umbes 1152","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Halsham, Yorkshire, England":"Halsham, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Thorp Arch, Yorkshire, England":"Thorp Arch, Yorkshire, England","Wra